\section{Experimental Objectives}


\subsection{RQ1: Scalability of Active Gaussian Payload Across Multiple Blocks}

\subsubsection{Research Question}

\textbf{RQ1: How does active Gaussian payload affect steady-state rendering
speed across multiple pretrained blocks on a fixed GPU?}

\subsubsection{Objective}

This experiment evaluates how steady-state rendering performance changes as
the active Gaussian payload increases. Unlike the preliminary single-block
evaluation, the final experiment uses five independently pretrained blocks to
measure whether the observed payload--performance relationship remains
consistent across different Gaussian spatial distributions.

The experiment addresses payload scalability only. GPU-memory normalisation,
cross-hardware comparison, and the derivation of a deployment threshold are
reserved for subsequent research questions.

\subsubsection{Experimental Setup}

The evaluation was conducted using five pretrained Gaussian blocks:

\begin{itemize}
    \item \texttt{gaussians\_016},
    \item \texttt{gaussians\_017},
    \item \texttt{gaussians\_026},
    \item \texttt{gaussians\_027}, and
    \item \texttt{gaussians\_028}.
\end{itemize}

Each block contained $50{,}000$ Gaussians, and each Gaussian record occupied
44 bytes. The experiments were performed on an NVIDIA RTX 5000 Ada Generation
GPU with approximately 32~GB of VRAM and CUDA compute capability 8.9.

All rendering parameters were held constant across blocks, payload levels,
and repetitions. The fixed settings are summarised in
Table~\ref{tab:rq1_multiblock_settings}.

\begin{table}[H]
\centering
\caption{Fixed rendering settings for the multi-block RQ1 experiment.}
\label{tab:rq1_multiblock_settings}
\begin{tabular}{lc}
\toprule
Parameter & Value \\
\midrule
GPU & NVIDIA RTX 5000 Ada Generation \\
Image resolution & $128 \times 128$ \\
Depth samples per ray & 64 \\
Vertical field of view & $90^{\circ}$ \\
Camera position & $(0,0,0)$ \\
Camera rotation & $(0^{\circ},0^{\circ},0^{\circ})$ \\
Rendering bounds & $[-1,1]^3$ \\
Tile size & $16 \times 16$ \\
Mahalanobis cutoff & 20 \\
Warm-up frames & 20 \\
Measured frames & 300 \\
Timing repetitions & 5 \\
Gaussians per full block & $50{,}000$ \\
Bytes per Gaussian & 44 \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

\subsubsection{Payload Construction}

For each block, one fixed shuffled Gaussian ordering was generated using a
constant random seed. This prevents the experiment from depending on the
original ordering of the Gaussian records.

The same ordering was reused for every payload level and every timing
repetition. Consequently, the subsets for each block were nested:

\begin{equation}
\mathcal{G}^{(b)}_{10\%}
\subset
\mathcal{G}^{(b)}_{20\%}
\subset
\mathcal{G}^{(b)}_{30\%}
\subset
\cdots
\subset
\mathcal{G}^{(b)}_{100\%},
\end{equation}

where $b$ denotes a block.

The evaluated retention ratios were

\begin{equation}
\rho \in
\left\{
0.10,
0.20,
0.30,
0.40,
0.50,
0.60,
0.75,
1.00
\right\}.
\end{equation}

For each block and retention ratio, the active Gaussian population was

\begin{equation}
N_{\mathrm{active}}
=
\rho N_{\mathrm{full}},
\end{equation}

where

\begin{equation}
N_{\mathrm{full}}=50{,}000.
\end{equation}

The raw active payload was calculated as

\begin{equation}
B_{\mathrm{active}}
=
N_{\mathrm{active}}
\times
44\text{ bytes}.
\end{equation}

The resulting raw payload was approximately 0.210~MiB at $5{,}000$
Gaussians and 2.098~MiB at $50{,}000$ Gaussians.

\subsubsection{Timing Protocol}

Renderer construction and preprocessing were excluded from steady-state
timing. The excluded stages were:

\begin{itemize}
    \item Gaussian binary loading,
    \item subset generation,
    \item CUDA allocation,
    \item host-to-device transfer,
    \item Gaussian preprocessing,
    \item tile binning,
    \item prefix scan,
    \item Gaussian--tile duplication,
    \item radix sorting,
    \item tile-range construction,
    \item output download, and
    \item image and CSV writing.
\end{itemize}

For every block and payload level, 20 untimed warm-up frames were rendered.
This was followed by 300 individually timed frames using CUDA events. Every
configuration was repeated five times.

The total number of benchmark runs was therefore

\begin{equation}
5\text{ blocks}
\times
8\text{ payload levels}
\times
5\text{ repetitions}
=
200\text{ runs}.
\end{equation}

For each measured frame $j$, rendering speed was calculated as

\begin{equation}
\mathrm{FPS}_j
=
\frac{1000}{T_j},
\end{equation}

where $T_j$ is the frame time in milliseconds.

The primary outcome was median FPS. Median render time, fifth-percentile FPS,
Gaussian--tile pair count, and variation across repeated measurements were
also recorded.

