The complete multi-block experiment contains 200 measurements covering all
five blocks, eight payload ratios, and five repetitions. 
\subsubsection{Rendering Performance}

Figure~\ref{fig:rq1_fps_gaussians} shows the effect of active Gaussian count
on rendering speed across all five pretrained blocks. FPS decreases
monotonically as the active payload increases, with a similar trend observed
for every block.

\begin{figure}[H]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[
        width=0.88\textwidth
    ]{/root/project/scripts/render_scripts/RQ1/results/rq1_multiblock/figures/rq1_fps_vs_active_gaussians.pdf}
    \caption{
        Median rendering speed as a function of active Gaussian count across
        five pretrained blocks. Each point represents the mean of the median
        FPS values obtained from five repeated runs, where each run contains
        300 measured frames following 20 warm-up frames. Error bars on the
        individual block curves indicate variation across timing repetitions,
        while the aggregate curve shows variation across blocks.
    }
    \label{fig:rq1_fps_gaussians}
\end{figure}
\subsubsection{Payload--Performance Relationship}

Figure~\ref{fig:rq1_time_gaussians} presents the same experiment in terms of
rendering time. Unlike FPS, frame time exhibits an approximately linear
relationship with active Gaussian count, making this representation more
appropriate for analysing computational scalability.

\begin{figure}[H]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[
        width=0.88\textwidth
    ]{/root/project/scripts/render_scripts/RQ1/results/rq1_multiblock/figures/rq1_render_time_vs_active_gaussians.pdf}
    \caption{
        Median rendering time as a function of active Gaussian count for five
        pretrained blocks. Individual curves show block-specific results, and
        the thicker aggregate curve shows the cross-block mean. The dashed
        line represents the pooled linear fit. Rendering time increases
        approximately linearly with the number of active Gaussians.
    }
    \label{fig:rq1_time_gaussians}
\end{figure}


Rendering time increased monotonically as the active Gaussian population
increased. Across the five blocks, increasing the payload from $5{,}000$ to
$50{,}000$ Gaussians increased the mean median frame time from approximately

\begin{equation}
3.03\text{ ms}
\end{equation}

to

\begin{equation}
29.55\text{ ms}.
\end{equation}

Over the same range, mean median rendering speed decreased from approximately

\begin{equation}
330.58\text{ FPS}
\end{equation}

to

\begin{equation}
33.87\text{ FPS}.
\end{equation}

Thus, increasing the active Gaussian population by a factor of ten produced
an approximately tenfold increase in frame time.

The inverse relationship between FPS and rendering time explains the
nonlinear FPS curve:

\begin{equation}
\mathrm{FPS}
=
\frac{1000}{T_{\mathrm{render}}}.
\end{equation}

For example, increasing the Gaussian count from $5{,}000$ to $10{,}000$
approximately doubled the aggregate frame time from 3.03~ms to 6.05~ms and
approximately halved FPS from 330.58 to 165.58.

\subsubsection{Block-Level Results}

Table~\ref{tab:rq1_full_payload_blocks} reports the performance of each block
at the full $50{,}000$-Gaussian payload.

\begin{table}[H]
\centering
\caption{Block-level performance at the complete Gaussian payload.}
\label{tab:rq1_full_payload_blocks}
\begin{tabular}{lrrr}
\toprule
Block &
Gaussian--Tile Pairs &
Median Time (ms) &
Median FPS \\
\midrule
\texttt{gaussians\_016} & 761,972 & 29.337 & 34.09 \\
\texttt{gaussians\_017} & 736,767 & 28.111 & 35.57 \\
\texttt{gaussians\_026} & 800,128 & 30.885 & 32.38 \\
\texttt{gaussians\_027} & 773,308 & 29.854 & 33.50 \\
\texttt{gaussians\_028} & 771,490 & 29.584 & 33.80 \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

Although all blocks contained the same number of Gaussians and the same raw
payload size, their rendering times differed. At the full payload,
\texttt{gaussians\_026} generated 800,128 Gaussian--tile pairs and rendered
at approximately 32.38 FPS. In contrast, \texttt{gaussians\_017} generated
736,767 pairs and rendered at approximately 35.57 FPS.

This result shows that Gaussian count alone does not completely determine
rendering cost. The projected spatial coverage of the Gaussians, represented
by the Gaussian--tile pair count, also affects the amount of work performed by
the rendering kernel.

Although Gaussian count captures the dominant scalability trend, blocks with
the same number of active Gaussians do not always require exactly the same
rendering time. Figure~\ref{fig:rq1_time_pairs} therefore relates frame time
to the number of Gaussian--tile pairs generated during preprocessing.

\begin{figure}[H]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[
        width=0.88\textwidth
    ]{/root/project/scripts/render_scripts/RQ1/results/rq1_multiblock/figures/rq1_render_time_vs_tile_pairs.pdf}
    \caption{
        Relationship between Gaussian--tile pair count and median rendering
        time across all blocks and payload levels. Each marker represents one
        block at one payload ratio after aggregation across five timing
        repetitions. The fitted regression line demonstrates that projected
        tile coverage explains residual block-specific performance differences
        not captured by Gaussian count alone.
    }
    \label{fig:rq1_time_pairs}
\end{figure}


Figure~\ref{fig:rq1_full_payload_blocks} compares the five blocks when all
$50{,}000$ Gaussians are active.

\begin{figure}[H]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[
        width=0.82\textwidth
    ]{/root/project/scripts/render_scripts/RQ1/results/rq1_multiblock/figures/rq1_full_payload_block_comparison.pdf}
    \caption{
        Full-payload median rendering time for the five pretrained blocks.
        All blocks contain $50{,}000$ active Gaussians, but their rendering
        costs differ because their Gaussian--tile pair counts and projected
        spatial coverage are not identical.
    }
    \label{fig:rq1_full_payload_blocks}
\end{figure}

\subsubsection{Scalability Models}

A separate linear model was fitted to each block:

\begin{equation}
T_{\mathrm{render}}^{(b)}
=
\beta_0^{(b)}
+
\beta_1^{(b)}
N_{\mathrm{active}}
+
\epsilon.
\end{equation}

The resulting slopes are shown in
Table~\ref{tab:rq1_block_regression}.

\begin{table}[H]
\centering
\caption{Block-specific linear scalability models.}
\label{tab:rq1_block_regression}
\begin{tabular}{lrr}
\toprule
Block &
Additional Time per 1,000 Gaussians (ms) &
$R^2$ \\
\midrule
\texttt{gaussians\_016} & 0.584 & 0.99996 \\
\texttt{gaussians\_017} & 0.560 & 0.99999 \\
\texttt{gaussians\_026} & 0.614 & 0.99992 \\
\texttt{gaussians\_027} & 0.594 & 0.99991 \\
\texttt{gaussians\_028} & 0.591 & 0.99994 \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

All five blocks exhibited an almost perfectly linear relationship between
active Gaussian count and rendering time, with block-specific $R^2$ values
greater than 0.9999.

Across the blocks, the rendering-time increase ranged from approximately

\begin{equation}
0.560\text{ ms}
\end{equation}

to

\begin{equation}
0.614\text{ ms}
\end{equation}

for every additional $1{,}000$ Gaussians.

A pooled linear model with block-specific intercepts produced

\begin{equation}
T_{\mathrm{render}}
\approx
0.019
+
5.8871 \times 10^{-4}
N_{\mathrm{active}}
+
\gamma_b,
\end{equation}

where \texttt{gaussians\_016} is the reference block and $\gamma_b$
represents the block-specific intercept adjustment.

The pooled model achieved

\begin{equation}
R^2 \approx 0.99905
\end{equation}

with an RMSE of approximately

\begin{equation}
0.253\text{ ms}.
\end{equation}

The fitted common slope corresponds to approximately

\begin{equation}
0.589\text{ ms}
\end{equation}

per additional $1{,}000$ active Gaussians.

Figure~\ref{fig:rq1_normalised_scaling} compares the relative scaling
behaviour of the five blocks after normalising each block by its own
full-payload rendering time.

\begin{figure}[H]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[
        width=0.82\textwidth
    ]{/root/project/scripts/render_scripts/RQ1/results/rq1_multiblock/figures/rq1_normalised_time_vs_retention.pdf}
    \caption{
        Render time normalised by the full-payload render time for each block.
        The close alignment of the block curves indicates that the relative
        payload-scaling behaviour is consistent across the five pretrained
        representations. The dashed reference indicates ideal linear scaling
        with retained Gaussian percentage.
    }
    \label{fig:rq1_normalised_scaling}
\end{figure}

\subsubsection{Qualitative Reconstruction Check}

Figure~\ref{fig:rq1_qualitative_reconstructions} presents representative
rendering outputs from the five pretrained blocks at selected Gaussian
retention ratios. The figure is included as a qualitative sanity check to
confirm that the timed configurations produce valid reconstructions
throughout the payload sweep. A shared linear grayscale is used across
all panels so that payload-dependent changes in the rendered response remain
visible.

\begin{figure}[H]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[
        width=0.98\textwidth
    ]{/root/project/scripts/render_scripts/RQ1/results/rq1_multiblock/figures/rq1_qualitative_reconstructions.pdf}
    \caption{
        Representative rendering outputs for the five pretrained blocks at
        10\%, 50\%, and 100\% Gaussian retention. Each row corresponds to a
        retained payload level and each column to one pretrained block. All
        panels use the same linear grayscale MIP-response scale.
    }
    \label{fig:rq1_qualitative_reconstructions}
\end{figure}

\subsubsection{Cross-Block Variation}

Variation between blocks increased moderately as the Gaussian payload
increased. At the 10\% payload, the standard deviation of median FPS across
blocks was approximately 11.66 FPS. At the complete payload, the corresponding
standard deviation was approximately 1.15 FPS.

The absolute FPS spread became smaller at high payloads because FPS is
inversely related to frame time. However, block-specific differences remained
visible in rendering time and Gaussian--tile pair count.

The full-payload frame times ranged from approximately

\begin{equation}
28.11\text{ ms}
\end{equation}

to

\begin{equation}
30.89\text{ ms}.
\end{equation}

This corresponds to a difference of approximately 9.9\% between the fastest
and slowest blocks despite identical Gaussian counts and payload sizes.

Consequently, active Gaussian count is a strong first-order predictor of
rendering cost, while projected tile coverage explains the residual
block-to-block variation.

\subsubsection{Repeatability}

The five timing repetitions for most configurations exhibited very low
variation. At the complete payload, the fifth-percentile FPS was nearly equal
to the median FPS for every block. Across all five blocks, the mean median FPS
was 33.87, while the mean fifth-percentile FPS was 33.86.

This small difference indicates that steady-state rendering performance was
temporally stable after the warm-up period.

A limited number of early low-payload repetitions contained slightly slower
frames, but these deviations did not affect the monotonic payload trend or
the fitted scalability models.

\subsubsection{Answer to RQ1}

The multi-block results show that active Gaussian payload has a strong,
monotonic, and approximately linear effect on steady-state rendering time on
the fixed GPU.

For every evaluated block,

\begin{equation}
T_{\mathrm{render}}
\propto
N_{\mathrm{active}}.
\end{equation}

Across the five blocks, each additional $1{,}000$ active Gaussians increased
frame time by approximately 0.560--0.614~ms. As a consequence, FPS decreased
reciprocally as the payload increased.

The experiment also showed that blocks with equal Gaussian counts can have
different rendering costs because their Gaussian--tile pair counts differ.
Therefore, Gaussian count determines the dominant scalability trend, while
the projected spatial coverage of the Gaussians explains the smaller
block-specific deviations.

The answer to RQ1 is therefore:

\begin{quote}
Across five pretrained blocks rendered on the same GPU under identical
settings, steady-state rendering time increased approximately linearly with
active Gaussian payload. The dominant scaling factor was the number of active
Gaussians, while Gaussian--tile pair count accounted for residual performance
differences between blocks. Consequently, FPS decreased approximately
reciprocally as the active payload increased.
\end{quote}


